                        </p>
                        <p><font face="Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif" size="3" color="black"><DIV>
                           <P style="MARGIN-BOTTOM: 0cm" align=left><FONT face=Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif><SPAN style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; COLOR: black;
                           FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><SPAN><SPAN style="FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><FONT color=#000000 face=Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif>"I
                           apprehend that if all living Union soldiers were summoned to the witness stand, every one of them would testify that it was
                           the preservation of the American Union and not the destruction of Southern slavery that induced him to volunteer at the call
                           of his Country. As for the South, it is enough to say that perhaps eighty percent of her armies were neither <a href="http://thomaslegion.net/causes.html" target="tlx_new"><font  color="black"><FONT color=#0000ff>slave-holders</FONT></font></a>, nor had the remotest interest in the institution...both sides fought and suffered for liberty as bequeathed by the Fathers--the
                           one for liberty in the union of the States, the other for liberty in the independence of the States." <EM>Reminiscences of
                           the Civil War</EM>, by John B. Gordon, Maj. Gen. CSA&nbsp;(</FONT></SPAN></SPAN><SPAN><SPAN style="FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; FONT-SIZE:
                           10pt"><FONT color=#000000 face=Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif><SPAN><SPAN style="FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><FONT
                           color=#000000 face=Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif>General Gordon was shot 5 times during the <a href="http://thomaslegion.net/war.html" target="tlx_new"><font  color="black"><FONT color=black><FONT color=#0000ff>Battle of Antietam</FONT></FONT></font></a> but did not die until January 9, 1904. R<FONT size=3><FONT size=2>egarding General John Gordon, President Theodore Roosevelt
                           stated, "A more gallant, generous, and fearless gentleman and soldier has not been seen by our Country.")</FONT></FONT></FONT></SPAN></SPAN></FONT></SPAN></SPAN></SPAN></FONT>
                           <!--"''"--></P></DIV></font>
                        </p>
